<br>
My question to you readers and people is this, friends and strangers alike:<br>
<br>
Why do you think that deserving an epic has to do with me sitting in front of my computer until I lapse into a catatonic state?<br>
<br>
Merit?  I don't know, that word we have agreed is very misleading sometimes.<br>
<br>
I'm a cleric, through and through.  I switched classes to cleric from magician because I truly enjoy helping others.  From simple things, like ressing a corpse next to me or buffing a newbie who asks, to getting a COH down to Disco in sebilis to res a group or helping out a younger raiding guild.<br>
<br>
*I* want my epic so that *I* am more useful and helpful.  I want to be able to zone into Fear and res 20 corpses in 5 minutes.  I want to be able to res that corpse at the seb ramp without having to ask my group to wait a minute.  Yes, it has nice stats.  Would I still want it just as much if it were an item without stats that could be used from the inventory?  Probably!<br>
<br>
But back to my question; *WHY* in the WORLD do you think me deserving my epic has to do with whether or not I've spent the last 72 hours awake in SolB?<br>
<br>
Food for thought, and oh.  /auction wtt Donals bp and legs for epic, assuming guild won't burn me alive!<br>
<br>
~Jason, Naeron, 59th level cleric with quite a few resses under his belt.<br>
